In the current unit there are also two large pieces of thoracic vertebra. Other (more fragmentary) cattle-sized material includes a femoral head, molar root, ulna shaft, a few cranial fragments, and around ten long bone splinters. Once again, the sheep-sized material appears much less selective. The sample is too small to expect full anatomical representation, but there does seem to be a bias against cranial elements, with only a single caprine upper molar, a few miscellaneous tooth and cranial fragments, a hyoid and three small pieces of mandible, plus a fragmented sheep horn core. All the long bones are represented by at least one specimen, along with atlas, astragalus, calcaneus and phalanges (only three fragments) plus around 25 long bone splinters and almost as many rib pieces. The most notable sheep-sized specimens, however, are an articulated group of two goat lumbar vertebrae and a sacrum, all partly calcined (i.e. grey rather than white). As with other fills in this space, the vast majority of specimens are burnt, although around 5% show no obvious signs of burning. Once again, a variety of burning conditions are represented, but compared to the overlying (16469) carbonization and extreme calcination are somewhat rarer in (16478) (around 10% and 5% of fragments respectively) with more bones either superficially burnt or calcined but grey. This may represent some of the material on the floor becoming shielded from further burning - and particularly oxidation - in the initial phases of collapse. Gnawing and digestion are each represented by only a few cases. Surface condition is obviously heavily influenced by the extent of burning, but is generally good, with most specimens at stage 3 (â€˜slight weathering) and 10-15% at stage 4 (moderate weathering). Burning has obscured any possible differences in patination that might have indicated the degree of heterogeneity in taphonomic histories prior to the destruction of the building. Flot (S2, >4mm, 100%): the flot is fairly small at around 80 fragments. It consists mainly of small, indeterminate specimens and scapula/rib pieces in a range of conditions consistent with the dry-sieved sample, plus a single equid incisor. Overall summary: the origin of the material seems likely to have been varied. Antlers, cattle horn cores, and cattle-sized scapulae and ribs are common in Building 77, often having apparently been on the floor at the point of collapse, whether placed there or fallen from the walls, ceiling, or internal features. The large cattle-sized pieces in the current unit should probably be explained in these terms, whether representing deliberate placements or simply raw materials ready for working. The presence of several cattle rib fragments within bone cluster (16483) on the floor of the southern part of Space 337 - immediately underlying the current unit - supports this suggestion. The articulated goat sacral/lumbar unit is clearly also primary and seems likely to have been in situ on the space floor. The remainder of the sheep-sized fraction, however, has very low integrity, making its inclusion in the unit harder to explain. The small volume of material militates against an interpretation in terms of dumping in the space prior to burning. Similarly low-integrity assemblages were recovered from various small bin fills in contact with this unit - (16496, 17502, 17503) - and interpreted as background noise. That in (16478) consists of rather too substantial pieces for this explanation, however, and even the flot lacks the usual tiny crumbles. The near-absence of head and feet (and paucity of axial elements in general) in favour of meaty limb parts is also noteworthy, suggesting a possible post-consumption character, although there is an absence of butchery marks. If the bulk of the sheep-sized material does represent post-consumption waste, it would seem to be the partial remnants of a larger assemblage, and thus presumably not an absolutely primary deposit. NR 2009: Sample 5 >4mm flotation 100% sorted, recorded as flot frags only. It was taken from close to a patch of grain. It is a smallish sample, with no diagnostics but a high proportion of large mammal scrap, including biggish pieces of rib and scapula. Also some sheep-size rib. Very little digestion, all burnt, moslty carbonized and calcined. Less fragmented than most. Seems to be catching fragments of dumped material in clean fill. Sample 6 is listed as having no bone in the 4mm (although so are Samples 2 and 5, oddly).
David Orton, Nerissa Russell (special finds, 1 flot)
